I've reviewed the changes in PR #365 and found several issues that should be addressed:

**1. Debug Print Statements in Production Code**

There are numerous debug print statements in `Polyfit.h` that should be removed before merging to production. Debug statements can impact performance and clutter logs in production environments.

```cpp
std::cout << "Debug: xMean = " << xMean << ", xStd = " << xStd << ", yMean = " << yMean << ", yStd = " << yStd << std::endl;

// Multiple other debug prints throughout the file
std::cout << "Debug: Regularization parameter lambda = " << lambda << std::endl;
std::cout << "Debug: Coefficients:" << std::endl;
std::cout << "Debug: Determinant before LU decomposition: " << det << std::endl;
```

Recommendation: Remove all debug print statements or wrap them in conditional compilation directives (e.g., `#ifdef DEBUG`) to ensure they don't appear in release builds.

**2. Duplicate Code in Polyfit.h**

There is duplicate code for scaling input data in `Polyfit.h`. The same operations are performed twice with slightly different variable names:

```cpp
// First instance
T xMean = std::accumulate(oX.begin(), oX.end(), T(0)) / oX.size();
T xStd = std::sqrt(std::inner_product(oX.begin(), oX.end(), oX.begin(), T(0)) / oX.size() - xMean * xMean);
T yMean = std::accumulate(oY.begin(), oY.end(), T(0)) / oY.size();
T yStd = std::sqrt(std::inner_product(oY.begin(), oY.end(), oY.begin(), T(0)) / oY.size() - yMean * yMean);

// Second instance
T x_mean = std::accumulate(oX.begin(), oX.end(), T(0)) / nCount;
T x_std = std::sqrt(std::inner_product(oX.begin(), oX.end(), oX.begin(), T(0)) / nCount - x_mean * x_mean);
T y_mean = std::accumulate(oY.begin(), oY.end(), T(0)) / nCount;
T y_std = std::sqrt(std::inner_product(oY.begin(), oY.end(), oY.begin(), T(0)) / nCount - y_mean * y_mean);
```

Recommendation: Refactor to calculate these values only once and reuse them throughout the function.

**3. Double Regularization Application**

The regularization term is applied twice to the matrix in `Polyfit.h`:

```cpp
// First application
const T lambda = 1e-8; // Adjusted regularization parameter
for (size_t i = 0; i < oXtXMatrix.size1(); ++i) {
    oXtXMatrix(i, i) += lambda;
}

// Second application
// Add regularization term to oXtXMatrix
for (size_t i = 0; i < oXtXMatrix.size1(); ++i) {
    oXtXMatrix(i, i) += lambda;
}
```

This double application of regularization could lead to numerical instability by making the regularization effect stronger than intended.

Recommendation: Apply regularization only once at the appropriate point in the algorithm.

## PR Review for #365

I've reviewed the changes and found the following issues:

### 1. Debug Print Statements in Production Code
Numerous debug print statements should be removed or conditionally compiled:
```cpp
std::cout << "Debug: xMean = " << xMean << ", xStd = " << xStd << ", yMean = " << yMean << ", yStd = " << yStd << std::endl;
// And many other similar statements throughout the file
```
Recommendation: Remove all debug prints or wrap them in `#ifdef DEBUG` directives.

### 2. Duplicate Data Scaling Logic & Double Regularization
The input data scaling calculation is performed twice and regularization is applied twice to the same matrix:
```cpp
// Duplicate scaling calculations
// First occurrence
T xMean = std::accumulate(oX.begin(), oX.end(), T(0)) / oX.size();
// ...
// Second occurrence
T x_mean = std::accumulate(oX.begin(), oX.end(), T(0)) / nCount;

// Double regularization
// First application
const T lambda = 1e-8;
for (size_t i = 0; i < oXtXMatrix.size1(); ++i) {
    oXtXMatrix(i, i) += lambda;
}
// Second application later in the code
for (size_t i = 0; i < oXtXMatrix.size1(); ++i) {
    oXtXMatrix(i, i) += lambda;
}
```
Recommendation: Calculate scaling values only once and remove one of the regularization loops.

### 3. Inconsistent Brace Style
The PR introduces inconsistent brace styles:
```cpp
// K&R style (braces on same line)
Extrapolator::T Extrapolator::Determinant() const {
    // ...
}

// Allman style (braces on new line) elsewhere
Extrapolator::solution_t Extrapolator::Solve(...) const
{
    // ...
}
```
Recommendation: Maintain consistent brace style throughout the codebase.

